<td id="title_text"><h1><a title="Electrophotography" class="currentChild" href="Electrophotography">Electrophotography</a></h1></td>



</tr></table>
</td>
</tr></table></div>



<div id="content" class="content wikipage" lang="en" dir="ltr">
<p id="l1">
A type of imaging system, commonly used in photocopiers, laser printers, etc., that utilizes an inorganic photoconductor—such as zinc oxide in electrofax, or selenium in xerography—applied to the surface of a drum. A corona sensitizes the drum to light using an electrostatic charge. Light reflected by non-image areas of the original image dissipates the charge from the non-image portions of the drum, the charge remaining in the image portions. A dry or liquid <a title="Toner" href="Toner">toner</a>, which is oppositely charged, is attracted to the charged (image) portions of the drum and adheres to it, transferring to paper (or other <a title="Substrate" href="Substrate">substrate</a>) passing beneath the drum. 
</p>
